fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.0dc2b08c-a73d-4e96-a638-cca5b69fb0d9.description=
This operation waits for the number of seconds specified in the "seconds" input.

Inputs\:
    seconds - The number of seconds to wait.

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the "completed sleep" message if the operation completed successfully and an error message otherwise. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.28c30dea-e968-4890-a5aa-34dce5f8af7e.description=
Issues 1 or more telnet commands via a RAS.

Inputs\:
    host - the host to connect to.
    port - the port to connect to.
    username - the username to use when connecting.
    password - the password to use when connecting.
    command - The command to execute. This should be made up of newline delimited statements of the format\:
	send 		//sends command to host
	expect 	//performs a regular expression match against the response from host, and proceeds to the next statement when it matches.
    usernamePrompt - the prompt that when seen should send the username.
    passwordPrompt - the prompt that when given should send the password.
    newlineCharacters - The character sequence to send as the enter key being pressed after each 'send' statement as the send expect script is processed in the command input. 
Valid values\:  \r\n, \n, \r or a comma delimited list of ASCII escape sequences.
Default value\: \n
    visualizer - Defines which screen simulator will be used for the result named "Visualized".  The default value is "basic" which emulates a vt100 terminal and return a XML document through "Visualized" where each screen is an element.  If "none" is specified "Visualized" will be empty.
    characterDelay - The delay in milliseconds between sending characters of the telnet commands. Also it is the delay between generating visualized result and recieving in-coming stream.
    characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the target machine. For example, SJIS,EUC-JP, UTF-8.  By default it is UTF-8.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Results\:
    returnResult - the raw output of the telnet session or an error message
    STDOUT - the raw output of the telnet session or the empty string. This is the primary output.

Extra Results\:
    visualized - the output of the command in XML format

Note\:
    For connecting to a Windows telnet server you may need to set the 'newlineCharacters' input to '\r\n'
fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.4158f9f1-32a4-49db-b1cf-2b0df3bf3c51.description=Sends a command to the telnet server. This should be preceded by Send Username and Send password in a telnet sequence. The last command in the sequence should have ICT_lastInSession set to true to close the session. This operation is not the preferred way to use telnet, RAS Telnet Shell is. 
Inputs\:
Command - The command to execute on the remote host.
ICT_Host - The host to execute the command on.
ICT_Port - The port telnet is running on.
ICT_Session - A unique name for the telnet session this command is run from.
ICT_WaitMode - How to wait for the response\: ''none'' - do not wait, ''any'' - wait for any response, ''match'' - wait for response to match the regular expression. Defaults to none.
ICT_TermExpr - The expression to match the server's response before sending the command.
ICT_LastInSession - If set to ''true'', this is deemed the last operation in the session. The session is terminated and removed from the context after this operation finishes.
ICT_Charset - The encoding used for the received characters (for instance ''MS932'' for Japanese Windows). Defaults to UTF-8.

Responses\:
success - Operation succeeded.
failure - Operation failed.

Returns - The standard output of the telnet command.

Authentication Note\:
Send Username and Send Password should preceded this operation to successfully establish a session.
fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.4d3d4a13-63f5-426d-87fa-c0be99f1f393.description=Counts from one number to another number. 
Inputs\:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE\: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns\:
The number that was just counted.

Note\: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses\:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.

fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.a60ccb08-8c34-4560-af07-247f75833ca7.description=
 
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable. 
    trimSpaces - If set on "true" then all the whitespaces will be removed from the value stored. 
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Returns\: 
    The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable with all whitespaces removed.

Responses\:
    isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
    notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned. 

Notes\: 
    1. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "true" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "isNull". 
    2. If the "trimSpaces" input is set on "false" and the value from "keyName" contains only whitespaces then the response will be "notNull". 
    3. If any other value than "true" or "false" is passed on "trimSpaces" input then the default value (false) will be used.
fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.a80f5c5f-e5ba-4084-9081-c45d766f13f6.description=
Sends the password to the telnet server.  This should be the second operation in a telnet sequence after Send Username.  It should be configured to wait for the telnet server to emit a password prompt prior to sending the password.

Inputs\:
Password - The password to send to the remote host.
ICT_Host - The host to execute the command on.
ICT_Port - The port telnet is running on.
ICT_Session - A unique name for the telnet session this command is run from.
ICT_PwdWaitMode - How to wait for the response\: ''none'' - do not wait, ''any'' - wait for any response, ''match'' - wait for response to match the regular expression. Defaults to none. Should be "match" to wait for a password prompt
ICT_PwdTermExpr - The expression to match the server's response before sending the command.  This should match the password prompt of the target server.
ICT_LastInSession - If set to ''true'', this is deemed the last operation in the session. The session is terminated and removed from the context after this operation finishes.  This should typically be false for Send Password.
ICT_Charset - The encoding used for the received characters (for instance ''MS932'' for Japanese Windows). Defaults to UTF-8.

Responses\:
success - Operation succeeded.
failure - Operation failed.

Returns - The standard output of the telnet command.

Authentication Note\:
By default this operation expects a "Password\: " or "password\: " prompt.  If the target system has a different password prompt this operation will need to be copied and modified to expect the appropriate password prompt.  After copying this operation to a writable folder, modify the regular expression in the "ICT_PwdTermExpr" input that will match the password prompt on the target system. Then modify the "Output String" rule for the success response to not match a new login prompt or the message of the day after a successful login to the system.
fae7d4a0-e869-41a3-8b60-ff53ea4f127e.e3fdc0ef-7fea-4202-b018-8419eb25da9c.description=
Sends a username to the telnet server.  This should be the first operation in a telnet sequence and should be used to establish the telnet session.  It should be configured to wait for the telnet server to emit a login prompt prior to sending the username.

Inputs\:
Username - The username to send to the remote host.
ICT_Host - The host to execute the command on.
ICT_Port - The port telnet is running on.
ICT_Session - A unique name for the telnet session this command is run from.
ICT_UserWaitMode - How to wait for the response\: ''none'' - do not wait, ''any'' - wait for any response, ''match'' - wait for response to match the regular expression. Defaults to none. Should be "match" to wait for a login prompt.
ICT_UserTermExpr - The expression to match the server's response before sending the command. This should match the login prompt of the target server.
ICT_LastInSession - If set to ''true'', this is deemed the last operation in the session. The session is terminated and removed from the context after this operation finishes. This should typically be false for Send Username.
ICT_Charset - The encoding used for the received characters (for instance ''MS932'' for Japanese Windows). Defaults to UTF-8.

Responses\:
success - Operation succeeded.
failure - Operation failed.

Returns - The standard output of the telnet command.

Authentication Note\:
By default this operation expects a "Login\: " or "login\: " prompt.  If the target system has a different login prompt this operation will need to be copied and modified to expect the appropriate login prompt.  After copying this operation to a writable folder, modify the regular expression in the "ICT_UserTermExpr" input that will match the login prompt on the target system.
